//What is the difference between var, let, and const?

//var is function scoped and allows redeclaration and reassignment.
// let is block scoped and allows reassignment but not redeclaration.
// const is block scoped and allows neither redeclaration nor reassignment.


//What is the Hoisting in JavaScript?

//"Hoisting is JavaScript's behavior of moving declarations
// to the top of their scope during the memory creation phase.

// Variables declared with var are initialized as undefined,
// while let and const remain in the Temporal Dead Zone until initialized.
// Function declarations are completely hoisted with their definitions."


// What is the difference between function scope and block scope? How does it relate to var vs let/const?

// "var is function scoped, meaning it is accessible throughout the entire function.
// let and const are block scoped, meaning they exist only inside the nearest { } block.
// This is why let/const provide better control and avoid unintended access or bugs."


// Can we change the value of a const variable? Explain with an example.

// "No, a const variable cannot be reassigned after declaration.
// However, if the const variable stores an object or array,
// its internal properties/elements can still be modified
// because only the reference remains constant."

const user = {
    name: "Vaibhav",
    city: "Mumbai"
};

// Allowed
user.city = "Pune";
console.log(user);

const name = "Vaibhav";
// name = "Rahul";   //  Error
console.log(name); //TypeError: Assignment to constant variable.


// Var loop:
for (var i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
    setTimeout(() => console.log(i), 100);
}
// - var is function-scoped, not block-scoped
// - There is only ONE i variable shared across all iterations
// - The loop completes immediately, setting i to 3
// - When the timeouts execute after 100ms, they all reference the SAME i which is now 3
// - Output: 3, 3, 3

// Let loop:
for (let j = 0; j < 3; j++) {
    setTimeout(() => console.log(j), 100);
}
// - let is block-scoped
// - Each iteration of the for loop creates a NEW binding of j for that block
// - So each closure captures a different j value (0, 1, 2)
// - When timeouts execute, they reference their own captured j
// - Output: 0, 1, 2